<section class="card">
  <h2>About Beans</h2>

  <p class="tagline">
    Direct-sow warm-season crop—wait for soil warmth, not just the calendar.
  </p>

  <p class="lede">
    <strong>Beans are frost-tender and can be killed at 32°F (0°C).</strong>
    In short growing seasons, success depends less on starting early and more on planting into warm soil so the crop develops fast enough to finish before first frost.
  </p>

  <p>
    This is a climate-normal planning problem: your frost window sets the season length, and your seasonal heat budget determines how quickly beans move through flowering and pod fill.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>Quick Planning Reference</h2>

  <ul>
    <li><strong>Direct sow:</strong> 1–3 weeks after last frost (once soil is warm)</li>
    <li><strong>Days to maturity:</strong> 50–70 days (variety-dependent)</li>
    <li><strong>Frost tolerance:</strong> None (protect from all frost at 32°F / 0°C)</li>
  </ul>

  <p class="fine muted">
    These are practical ranges. Local conditions matter—especially soil temperature, wind exposure, and cold nights.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>Cold Sensitivity & Temperature Requirements</h2>

  <ul>
    <li><strong>Optimal growth:</strong> 70–85°F (21–29°C)</li>
    <li><strong>Slow growth:</strong> Below 60°F (16°C)</li>
    <li><strong>Germination minimum:</strong> About 55°F (13°C) soil temperature</li>
    <li><strong>Stress threshold:</strong> Below 50°F (10°C)</li>
    <li><strong>Freeze damage:</strong> 32°F (0°C)</li>
  </ul>

  <p>
    Beans don’t have a frost buffer. That makes first fall frost the hard seasonal stop, and it’s why “close enough” maturity timelines can still fail when early growth stalls.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>Planting Window Logic (Short Season)</h2>

  <p>
    Beans are one of the clearest examples of a crop where <strong>soil temperature matters more than calendar timing.</strong>
    Planting into cold soil can delay emergence and reduce the risk margin you need later.
  </p>

  <ul>
    <li><strong>Too early:</strong> slow germination, seed rot, uneven stands</li>
    <li><strong>On time:</strong> fast emergence, vigorous growth, earlier harvest</li>
    <li><strong>Too late:</strong> reduced buffer before fall frost</li>
  </ul>

  <p class="fine">
    If you want the “why” behind this framework, see:
    <a href="/guides/average-frost-date-vs-actual-weather/">Average frost date vs actual weather</a>.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>Fall Frost Cutoff Modeling</h2>

  <p>
    Because beans are killed at 32°F (0°C), the first fall frost is a hard cutoff. Your planting date needs enough runway for flowering and pod fill before that boundary.
  </p>

  <p>
    In short seasons, the most reliable approach is to:
  </p>

  <ul>
    <li>Choose earlier varieties (often 50–55 days)</li>
    <li>Plant promptly once soil is warm</li>
    <li>Avoid stalling early growth with cold soil or exposed sites</li>
  </ul>

  <div class="actions">
    <a class="button subtle" href="/tools/first-frost-planner/">Plan Backward From First Frost</a>
  </div>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>Typical GDD Requirement</h2>

  <p><strong>Base temperature:</strong> 50°F (10°C)</p>
  <p><strong>Approximate GDD needed:</strong> ~900–1,200 GDD (base 50) for most bush beans</p>

  <p>
    Growing Degree Days (GDD) describe how much seasonal heat accumulates in a typical year. Beans mature on a heat schedule:
    weak heat accumulation slows development and pushes maturity later, shrinking your frost buffer.
  </p>

  <p class="fine muted" style="margin-top:14px;">
    GDD = ((Daily High + Daily Low) ÷ 2) − 50
  </p>

  <div class="actions">
    <a class="button subtle" href="/tools/growing-degree-day-planner/">Use the GDD Planner</a>
  </div>

  <p class="fine">
    For how frost timing and GDD combine into one viability model, see:
    <a href="/guides/how-frost-dates-and-growing-degree-days-work-together/">How frost dates and Growing Degree Days work together</a>.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>Minimum Frost-Free Days</h2>

  <p>
    Most bush beans need roughly <strong>50–70 frost-free days</strong> to reach harvest. Pole beans typically need more time.
  </p>

  <p>
    If your frost-free window is tight, beans can still work—but variety selection and fast early growth become the deciding factors.
  </p>

  <div class="actions">
    <a class="button subtle" href="/tools/frost-date-finder/">Check Your Frost-Free Season</a>
  </div>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>Short-Season Viability Flag</h2>

  <ul>
    <li><strong>Good choice under 100 days?</strong> Yes (bush beans are a common short-season win)</li>
    <li><strong>Risky under 90 days?</strong> Often, unless you choose early varieties and your summer heat is reliable</li>
    <li><strong>Needs season extension?</strong> Sometimes helpful early (row cover for warmth), but beans are usually direct-sown</li>
  </ul>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>First Frost Sensitivity</h2>

  <p>
    Beans have <strong>no frost tolerance buffer</strong>. A freeze at 32°F (0°C) can end the crop immediately.
    That makes first frost the hard stop for maturity modeling.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>Early-Maturing Strategy</h2>

  <ul>
    <li>Choose early bush varieties (often 50–55 days)</li>
    <li>Wait for warm soil, then plant on time (cold soil delays everything)</li>
    <li>Prioritize full sun and wind shelter to protect heat accumulation</li>
    <li>Use light row cover early only to add warmth (not to push into frost)</li>
  </ul>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>Planning Model</h2>

  <p class="muted">
    Frost → Season Length → GDD → Crop Requirement → Risk Margin
  </p>

  <p>
    In a typical year, beans are viable when your frost-free window provides enough time and your seasonal heat budget provides enough GDD.
    If the model barely works on paper, treat it as low-buffer and choose earlier varieties.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>Summary</h2>

  <ul>
    <li>Beans are killed at 32°F (0°C), so first frost is a hard seasonal stop.</li>
    <li>Most bush beans fit a 50–70 day runway, but cold-soil delays reduce buffer.</li>
    <li>Heat accumulation matters: marginal seasonal GDD increases maturity risk.</li>
    <li>Short-season success comes from warm-soil planting + early varieties + risk margin.</li>
  </ul>
</section>